Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Can you clarify the issue? The idea of the thread_index-1 was that the same txq id and rxq id should land on the same core by default (ie txq #0 and rxq#0 on worker 0, txq #1 and rxq #1 on worker 1...) to avoid locking if possible.
It should probably be updated to take advantage of the new txq framewrok instead, but what is the bug exactly here?

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1
> 
> Can you clarify the issue? The idea of the thread_index-1 was that the same txq id and rxq id should land on the same core by default (ie txq #0 and rxq#0 on worker 0, txq #1 and rxq #1 on worker 1...) to avoid locking if possible.
> It should probably be updated to take advantage of the new txq framewrok instead, but what is the bug exactly here?

We has 11 rxq and 3 txq. vpp main is thread 0 and wrk 0 is thread 1, they are using the txq #0.

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> > Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1
> > 
> > Can you clarify the issue? The idea of the thread_index-1 was that the same txq id and rxq id should land on the same core by default (ie txq #0 and rxq#0 on worker 0, txq #1 and rxq #1 on worker 1...) to avoid locking if possible.
> > It should probably be updated to take advantage of the new txq framewrok instead, but what is the bug exactly here?
> 
> We has 11 rxq and 3 txq. vpp main is thread 0 and wrk 0 is thread 1, they are using the txq #0.

Main worker is using to send syn packet. Without lock, cq and tx idx will change unexpected and then packet can't send out.

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1
> 
> Can you clarify the issue? The idea of the thread_index-1 was that the same txq id and rxq id should land on the same core by default (ie txq #0 and rxq#0 on worker 0, txq #1 and rxq #1 on worker 1...) to avoid locking if possible.
> It should probably be updated to take advantage of the new txq framewrok instead, but what is the bug exactly here?

What is new txq framework? Should we use "thread_index - 1 + ad->txq_num) % ad->txq_num" to place the queues.

Patch Set 1:

> We has 11 rxq and 3 txq. vpp main is thread 0 and wrk 0 is thread 1, they are using the txq #0. 
> Main worker is using to send syn packet. Without lock, cq and tx idx will change unexpected and then packet can't send out.

Ok I think I got it: you have 1 main thread + 2 workers. We create 3 txqs == n_vlib_mains hence we do not initialize the txq lock (we have 1 txq per thread), but because of this -1 we end up sharing txq#0 without lock. You're right this is bogus... It works for power-of-2 but that's basically it...

> What is new txq framework?

It was introduced by https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/32004
Drivers can register their txqs to the framework so you have the flexibility as rxq for placement etc. plus other nice features in the future (such as being able to use multiple txqs from a single core).
If you are interested to tackle it for af_xdp that would be great :) - you can look at https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/33947 for an example.

> Should we use "thread_index - 1 + ad->txq_num) % ad->txq_num" to place the queues.

Yes I think it is the correct thing to do. Could you update your patch accordingly? Thanks a lot!

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> > We has 11 rxq and 3 txq. vpp main is thread 0 and wrk 0 is thread 1, they are using the txq #0. 
> > Main worker is using to send syn packet. Without lock, cq and tx idx will change unexpected and then packet can't send out.
> 
> Ok I think I got it: you have 1 main thread + 2 workers. We create 3 txqs == n_vlib_mains hence we do not initialize the txq lock (we have 1 txq per thread), but because of this -1 we end up sharing txq#0 without lock. You're right this is bogus... It works for power-of-2 but that's basically it...
> 
Yes, it is.

> > What is new txq framework?
> 
> It was introduced by https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/32004
> Drivers can register their txqs to the framework so you have the flexibility as rxq for placement etc. plus other nice features in the future (such as being able to use multiple txqs from a single core).
> If you are interested to tackle it for af_xdp that would be great :) - you can look at https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/33947 for an example.

Thanks, I will look into it.

> 
> > Should we use "thread_index - 1 + ad->txq_num) % ad->txq_num" to place the queues.
> 
> Yes I think it is the correct thing to do. Could you update your patch accordingly? Thanks a lot!
done.

 - remove dmax=4096 check from clib_strcpy and introduce clib_strcpy_s which have one more argument
 - modify clib_strcpy so caller needs to specify dmax.

I just realized there is zero invocations of clib_strcpy in our current code. So let’s get a rid of it….
